## Modifications

- `random/*.slt`: each upstream `random/select` and `random/aggregates` file
  is auto-generated and enormous (~11,000-14,000 query records per file,
  70,000-90,000 lines) - vendoring any one of them whole would dwarf
  select1-4 combined and make the baseline unreviewable. Kept the full
  `hash-threshold` + `CREATE TABLE`/`INSERT INTO` setup block (9 rows across
  3 tables) verbatim, then truncated to the first 150 subsequent records
  (query/statement blocks). This is a deliberate content truncation, not a
  content edit: no query text or expected result within a kept record was
  changed, and original line numbers of kept records are unchanged.
- All vendored files: reflowed multi-column, non-hashed `query` result
  blocks from the classic SQLite "one value per line" layout to "one row
  per line, values space-joined" layout (only for records where
  `sort_mode != valuesort`, the type string has >1 column, and the result
  block isn't already a single collapsed hash line). The `sqllogictest`
  Rust crate (0.29.1)'s default validator joins each *actual* result row
  with a single space and compares the resulting `Vec<String>` (one entry
  per row) directly against the raw lines read from the file (one entry
  per line); it does not group raw lines into rows by column count. The
  upstream files use the original one-value-per-line SQLite convention, so
  every multi-column query would otherwise report a spurious mismatch
  regardless of engine correctness. This is a vendoring-time reflow to
  match the comparison behavior of the specific runner crate version in
  use, not a change to any expected value. 736 result blocks were reflowed
  across select1-4, in1, in2, and the two `random/aggregates_*` files (see
  the vendoring commit for the exact script).
- `select1.slt`, `select4.slt`, `in1.slt`, `in2.slt`: prepended a
  `hash-threshold 8\n\n` header. These four upstream files omit the
  `hash-threshold` directive but still contain literal `N values hashing
  to <md5>` result lines (baked in by whatever threshold the original
  SQLite tooling used when the files were generated, evidently 8, matching
  the value present in the sibling files that do carry the directive).
  Without an explicit directive the `sqllogictest` crate defaults
  `hash_threshold` to 0 (i.e. never hash), so large non-hashed actual
  results would never match the pre-hashed expected lines. Prepending the
  directive restores the crate's behavior to match what the file's own
  expected results assume.
- All vendored files: stripped trailing inline `# comment` text from
  `onlyif <label>` / `skipif <label>` condition lines (320 lines across 7
  files: in1.slt, in2.slt, slt_lang_createview.slt, and the four
  `random/*.slt` files). The `sqllogictest` crate's line parser matches
  these directives via `["onlyif"|"skipif", label]` - i.e. it requires
  exactly two whitespace-separated tokens - and errors on the whole file
  ("invalid line") if a trailing comment is present. This mechanically
  strips comment text only; the condition keyword and label are untouched
  (`onlyif mysql # some comment` -> `onlyif mysql`).
- `select5.slt` is not vendored - see "Dropped files" below.

## Dropped files (not vendored) and reasons

- `test/select5.test`: every one of its 732 query records is labeled
  `join-N-M` and exercises multi-way implicit joins ranging from 4 to 64
  tables in a single `FROM t1,t2,...,tN WHERE <equalities>` clause. Without
  join-reordering, polars-sql lowers an N-way implicit join into a literal
  N-way cross product filtered by the WHERE clause; for N beyond roughly
  20 this is combinatorially intractable (e.g. a 24-way join over tables
  with a few dozen rows each attempts to materialize far more rows than
  fits in memory) and the harness process was OOM-killed partway through
  this file during Phase 2 triage (confirmed by bisection - the process
  completes select1-4 in seconds each but hangs/is killed inside
  select5.test specifically, at a `join-24-4` record). A hang has no
  representation in the `expected_failures.txt` ratchet (it can only mark
  bounded pass/fail outcomes), so the file cannot be used as conformance
  signal without risking CI availability. Dropped entirely rather than
  hand-picking a "safe" low-arity prefix, since the file's entire purpose
  is the high-arity stress test. This is a real, high-value finding for
  Phase 3 triage (see the vendoring commit message): naive N-way implicit
  join translation without reordering/decorrelation is a gap worth its own
  tracked item, independent of whether this specific corpus file is
  vendored.
- `test/evidence/slt_lang_dropindex.test`, `test/evidence/slt_lang_reindex.test`:
  require stateful index-existence tracking (DROP INDEX on an
  already-dropped / never-existed index must error, and `REINDEX` itself
  has no equivalent) to get the expected "statement error" records right.
  This conflicts with the Step 2 mandate to treat CREATE INDEX/DROP INDEX
  as unconditional no-ops in the shim. Adding per-index existence tracking
  just for these two small files was judged not worth the shim complexity;
  dropped rather than hacked.
- `test/evidence/slt_lang_droptable.test`: same issue - it requires
  `DROP TABLE` to error on an already-dropped/never-existed table and
  `DROP INDEX` to error because the owning table was dropped. Our shim's
  `DROP TABLE` is an unconditional no-op today; adding existence-checked
  DROP semantics only to satisfy this one DDL-focused file (it is not
  SELECT-relevant) wasn't worth it. Dropped.
- `test/evidence/slt_lang_createtrigger.test`, `slt_lang_droptrigger.test`:
  triggers are out of the agreed read-query-only scope (no INSERT/UPDATE
  side effects to fire). Dropped.
- `test/evidence/slt_lang_replace.test`: exercises `REPLACE INTO`
  (upsert), out of the read-query-only scope. Dropped.
- `test/evidence/slt_lang_update.test`: exercises `UPDATE`, out of the
  read-query-only scope. Dropped.
- `test/random/expr/*`, `test/random/groupby/*`: directories not sampled;
  `select` and `aggregates` random directories already give representative
  generated-query coverage within the record budget.
- All other `test/random/select/*.test` and `test/random/aggregates/*.test`
  files beyond the 2+2 sampled (`slt_good_0`, `slt_good_50` from each
  directory): not vendored, to keep the corpus size manageable.
  `slt_good_0`/`slt_good_50` were picked as a fixed, deterministic,
  spread-out sample rather than vendoring the full ~127/~130 file
  directories - each individual file already contains ~11,000-14,000
  query records, so even a handful of full files would dwarf the rest of
  the corpus.

## skipif polars divergences

`skipif polars` was added to 160 individual records (documented per
cluster below), all discovered during Phase 2 triage of the initial
baseline run. In every case the record's own SQL is unaffected; the
comment is placed as its own `skipif polars` line immediately above the
`query` line, matching the file's existing `skipif <engine>` style.

- **135 records** (select1.slt, select2.slt, select3.slt,
  random/aggregates_slt_good_{0,50}.slt, random/select_slt_good_{0,50}.slt):
  integer division. Polars SQL's `/` operator always performs true
  (floating-point) division regardless of operand types - a deliberate,
  pre-existing product decision (commit 18e3422118, "feat: Use true
  division for the `/` operator in Polars SQL (#27391)"), predating this
  harness. SQLite (and standard/PostgreSQL C-style truncating integer
  division) instead truncates `int / int` toward zero. This is an
  intentional, already-decided divergence, not a gap - e.g.
  `SELECT (a+b+c+d+e)/5 FROM t1` where all columns are INTEGER.
- **17 records** (in1.slt): boolean representation. SQLite has no
  distinct boolean type, so `1 IN (2)` evaluates to the SQLite convention
  of integer `0`/`1`. Polars SQL correctly evaluates this to a native
  Postgres-aligned boolean (`false`/`true`), which is what the harness
  formats. Intentional Postgres-alignment divergence.
- **8 records** (in2.slt): empty `IN ()` / `NOT IN ()` lists. Standard SQL
  (and PostgreSQL) require the parenthesized list to have at least one
  element and reject `x IN ()` as a syntax error; SQLite permits it as an
  extension (always `false`/`true` per the evidence file's own commentary,
  R-64309-54027). Aligning with PostgreSQL, we reject this syntax too.

## Not-yet-triaged as skipif (left in the baseline as missing features/bugs)

A few small clusters found in "query result mismatch" during triage are
real correctness gaps (not dialect divergences - SQLite and PostgreSQL
agree on the expected behavior), so they were left in
`expected_failures.txt` rather than marked `skipif polars`:
- IN/NOT IN with NULL in the list and no match should return NULL
  (three-valued logic), not false/true (in1.slt, in2.slt; ~7 records).
- Unary negation of `COUNT(*)`/`COUNT(expr)` produces an unsigned-integer
  wraparound (e.g. `-COUNT(*)` on a 3-row table renders as `4294967293`
  instead of `-3`), which then cascades through further arithmetic
  (random/aggregates_slt_good_{0,50}.slt; ~8 records).
- `SUM(<literal>)` (a constant, not a column expression) returns the
  literal itself instead of the literal multiplied by the row count
  (random/aggregates_slt_good_{0,50}.slt; 3 records).
- `SUM`/`MIN` over an all-NULL or empty (fully-filtered) group returns `0`
  or a placeholder instead of `NULL` (random/aggregates_slt_good_50.slt;
  3 records).
- A handful (~6 records, slt_lang_aggfunc.slt) of SQLite dynamic
  type-affinity edge cases (aggregating a TEXT-affinity column that holds
  numeric-looking string literals) that Polars' static per-column typing
  (like PostgreSQL's) cannot replicate; not considered fixable in this
  product, left baselined rather than skipif-tagged given the small,
  idiosyncratic count.

These, along with the missing-feature clusters (subqueries, chained set
operations, self-join column collisions, etc.), are ranked in the Phase 2
triage table in the vendoring commit message.
